"1330":"1330","about 1330":"about 1330","Of Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gascoigne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>Gascon</i>, Middle English <i>Gascoun</i>, <i>Gascon</i> ‘Gascon, native of Gascony’ or the adjective <i>Gascuinz</i> ‘of Gascony’. The name of the region derives from that of the Basques, who are found close by and formerly extended into this region as well; they are first named in Roman sources as <i>Vascōnes</i>, but the original meaning of the name derived from a root <i>eusk-</i> in the non-Indo-European language that they still speak today, is completely obscure. By the Middle Ages the Basques had been displaced from most of Gascony by speakers of Gascon (a dialect of Occitan, related to French), who were proverbial for their boastfulness. In the 11th century Gascony united with Aquitaine and was thus held by England between 1154 and 1453."],"variants":[{"name":"Gaskin","meanings":["English: variant of   Gascoigne  ."]},{"name":"Gascon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jaime, Mario, Miguel, Rafael, Ruben, Amado, Ana, Ana Maria, Angel, Caridad.  French Andre, Chantal, Jean-Guy, Jean-Philippe, Monique, Serge, Simonne.","French; Spanish (<b>Gascón</b>): habitational name for someone from the province of Gascony, Old French <i>Gascogne</i> (see   Gascoigne  ). This surname is also found in Britain."]},{"name":"Gascoyne","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Gascoigne  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Gascoigne was born about 1330, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1357–Female":"1357–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1357":"1357","1330":"1330","about 1330":"umbes 1330","Of Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1330–":"noin 1330–Kuollut","1357–Female":"1357–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1357":"1357","1330":"1330","about 1330":"noin 1330","Of Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1330–":"environ 1330–Décédé","1357–Female":"1357–Décédée","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1357":"1357","1330":"1330","about 1330":"environ 1330","Of Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir William Gascoigne est né environ 1330, à Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1330–":"um 1330–Verstorben","1357–Female":"1357–Verstorben","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1357":"1357","1330":"1330","about 1330":"um 1330","Of Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Sir William Gascoigne wurde um 1330 in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1330–":"about 1330–Desede","1357–Female":"1357–Desede","1330–Male":"1330–Desede","1357":"1357","1330":"1330","about 1330":"about 1330","Of Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"about 1330–":"1330 körül–elhunyt","1357–Female":"1357–elhunyt","1330–Male":"1330–elhunyt","1357":"1357","1330":"1330",